kup to exclude other causes of liver injury (e.g., viral hepatitis, biliary obstruction) is crucial, as emphasized by EASL [cite: EASL Clinical Practice Guidelines: Drug-induced liver injury-Laboratory Workup for Excluding Alternative Causes, p.1, https://storage.googleapis.com/easl-pdf/DILI.pdf]. Close daily monitoring of liver functiontests and INR is essential to assess response to treatment and detect any progression towards liver failure. If there is no response to corticosteroids within 2\\u20133 days, the addition of a second immunosuppressive agent like mycophenolate mofetil should be considered [cite: EASL Clinical Practice Guidelines: Drug-induced liver injury-Table5. Management of Immune-Mediated Liver Injury, p.1, https://storage.googleapis.com/easl-pdf/DILI.pdf].\", \"guideline_reference\": []}",
